    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:e57c6a9f-3635-48da-847c-80833ca45068",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 51-year-old woman who appears well groomed and slightly overweight, with a body habitus suggesting central adiposity. She works as an office manager for a regional insurance company, spending long hours seated at a computer and often eating lunch at her desk. Over the past few years she has noticed gradually reduced exercise tolerance, not from chest pain or breathlessness, but from deconditioning and weight gain. She reports no dramatic physical symptoms related to her lipid disorder and was prompted to seek care after a routine workplace wellness screening showed elevated cholesterol levels.\n\nIn conversation, {patientName} is practical, organized, and mildly worried because her mother had a stroke in her 60s. She lives with her spouse and one teenage daughter, and much of her free time is spent driving family members to activities, caring for an elderly parent, and catching up on household tasks. She enjoys gardening in spring and summer and occasionally meets friends for weekend walks, though these have become less frequent. Her diet includes many convenience foods, cheese, red meat several times a week, and frequent evening snacking when stressed.\n\nShe sleeps about 6 hours per night and describes her sleep as \"light\" and often interrupted by stress. She drinks 1 to 2 glasses of wine on most weekends, does not use recreational drugs, and quit smoking in her early 30s after a 10-pack-year history. She drinks several cups of coffee daily. She has been trying to make healthier choices, recently adding oatmeal for breakfast and considering a gym membership, but finds it difficult to maintain changes consistently.\n\nOn examination she is alert, cooperative, and in no acute distress. Her blood pressure is mildly elevated, and her weight places her in the overweight range. There are no xanthomas or corneal arcus noted, and cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are otherwise unremarkable. Overall, she presents as a realistic middle-aged adult with largely asymptomatic hyperlipidaemia discovered through screening in the context of sedentary lifestyle, dietary risk factors, and family cardiovascular risk."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0e978baa-2a87-4bf0-be98-37851f51b93a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of overweight status and intermittent elevated blood pressure readings but no known diabetes, chronic kidney disease, or established cardiovascular disease. She has never been hospitalized for myocardial infarction, stroke, or heart failure. Her past medical history includes seasonal allergic rhinitis and occasional mechanical low back pain related to prolonged sitting. She entered menopause around age 49, with associated sleep disturbance and mild hot flashes.\n\n{patientName} underwent routine annual primary care follow-up, where screening laboratory tests repeatedly showed elevated total cholesterol and LDL cholesterol over the last 2 years. She has not previously taken lipid-lowering therapy. She reports a largely sedentary work routine, irregular exercise, and a diet high in saturated fat and processed foods, though she has recently attempted modest dietary changes. She is a former smoker and quit approximately 20 years ago.\n\nShe has no known liver disease, pancreatitis, nephrotic syndrome, or untreated thyroid disease. There is no history of familial tendon xanthomas or premature known genetic lipid disorder, but family history is notable for vascular disease in first-degree relatives. She is motivated to reduce long-term cardiovascular risk and is open to lifestyle counseling."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
